            <span class="who">
                <span class="">Jacob Schwarzfitter</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="#schwarzfitterJ" start="2617.798" end="x">At the rr-station . . . , and we had to leave them . . . It was a freight station, not one for people, for freight. And so we were driven. We went over to the <a class="term" href="#vothG_lager">lager</a>, the few people who had remained. There they did not survive. Because at that instant, I shall tell you now further what has happened. At the instant when we were marching, I saw for the first time, after a lapse of three years,—Jewish women, parents, Jewish men and children. Those were interned Hungarian Jew. They were sent away from the <a class="term" href="#vothG_lager">lager</a>, and we moved into the <a class="term" href="#vothG_lager">lager</a>.</span>
        </li>
